n class=title> And So It Begins (A Story)</span><hr size=1> Natasha Dupaski sat in her cubicle staring at the wall, daydreaming. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> 30,000 years of civilization and the cubicle is the best they can come up with?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Natasha sighed. She knew she shouldn’t complain. After all, she was lucky to have this dead end job as a clerk in an out of the way corner of the mighty Omni-Tek organization. But, still, she could dream. <br>
<br>
She would dream. <br>
<br>
If it was not for her dreams, she would not have even been able to rise to the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> lofty</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> position of clerk. Others might mock the position and the salary, but Natasha was grateful for the step up in her life. But it didn’t mean she was satisfied. <br>
<br>
Natasha grew up poor in a sector of Omni 1’s trade district known as the &quot;Russian Quarter.&quot; What &quot;Russian&quot; meant, she was not sure, but if she was to believe the old folk tales, Russia was a country from a far away planet long destroyed by its own people tens of thousands of years ago. The survivors made their way here and started over. The story was too outlandish to be true, to be sure. But many of her &quot;people,&quot; as they often referred to themselves, believed this story deeply. Some even went so far as to have &quot;natural&quot; children rather than proper genetically engineered children. Natasha was glad that she had a proper Solitus body, even if she was raised in the &quot;low class family unit&quot; rather than the proper Omni-Tek education and development programs. She almost felt sorry for the poor, sickly, inbred miscretins who’s &quot;parents&quot; refused to comply with proper genetic engineering. <br>
<br>
Being raised as she was, she had actually learned to speak the &quot;Russian&quot; language first instead of the proper language. It was defiant the way her &quot;people&quot; rebelled against the Omni-Tek way of life and she hated it. It took her years to learn how to live correctly and speak the right language. She had to study hard and for many hours to achieve a proper education that would afford her the ability to get even this simple clerks job. Many of her &quot;people&quot; were proud of her, at how hard she worked and to be possibly the only person from the &quot;Russian Quarter&quot; to ever gain significant employment with Omni-Tek. <br>
<br>
But among the supporters were an equal number of critics who proclaimed her a sell-out and a traitor to her people and culture. Her father was among her critics. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Some &quot;culture.&quot; </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> She thought to herself. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Impoverished, beholden to ancient traditions outdated eons ago and singing their stupid songs in their stupid language with no future to speak of. They refuse to see the beautiful world that Omni-Tek strives to provide us. They are no better than the Clan scum.&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Natasha refused to be condemned to that life. <br>
<br>
She pushed aside the thoughts of her past, her origins. She wanted to concentrate on the future. A future she knew would be bright and successful. She began to read, again, through the file she had found, had been searching for. The file that would change her life. <br>
<br>
The daydream began to materialize. <br>
